entry.sense:
which cannot usually be separately translated in English, its force depending on the constructions which contain it (see further, LS, s.v.; WM, §xlii; M, Pr., 165 ff.; MM, VGT, s.v.). 
    In apodosis, 
      c. indic, impf. or aor., expressing what would be or would have been if (εἰ c. impf., aor. or plpf.) some condition were or had been fulfilled: Lk 7:39  17:6, Jo 5:46, Ga 1:10, Mt 12:7  24:43, I Co 2:8, Ac 18:14, I Jo 2:19, al. The protasis is sometimes understood (as also in cl.): Mt 25:27, Lk 19:23. In hypothetical sentences, expressing unreality, ἄν (as often in late writers, more rarely in cl.) is omitted: Jo 8:39  15:24 19:11, Ro 7:7, Ga 4:15; 
      c. opt., inf., ptcp. (cl.; v. LS, s.v.; M, Int., §275; M, Pr., 167:4). 

    In combination with conditional, relative, temporal, and final words; 
      as in cl., c. subj., 
        in protasis with εἰ, in Attic contr. ἐάν, q.v.; 
